        </div>
    </div>
</div>
                        
                        <p>For students who may not have heard the outside siren, Cavanaugh explained that Duke has a contingency plan.</p>
<p>"During specific events Duke has a multilayered and redundant notification system," he wrote. "It includes, email, text, social media, digital signs, web sites and if needed, sirens. Each of the systems are tested regularly as part of the institutions emergency management system."</p>
<p>Two weeks ago during the <a href="https://www.dukechronicle.com/article/2018/09/tornado-warning-issued-for-duke-durham" target="_blank">tornado warning</a>, the University sent out two Duke alerts—one at 7:37 a.m. that cleared 15 minutes later and one at 8:17 a.m that was canceled about half an hour later. Both Cavanaugh and Murphy said that an immediate notification to the campus was vital.</p>
<p>"Tornadoes are fast developing and always changing," Cavanaugh added. "The immediate need is to get the initial notification out."</p>
